==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fry
<hw>Fry</hw> <pr>(fr⟦imac⟧)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fried</conjf> <pr>(fr⟦imac⟧d)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Frying</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>frien</ets>, F.
<ets>frire</ets>, fr. L. frigere to roast, parch, <ets>fry</ets>, cf.
Gr. <?/, Skr. <ets>bhrajj</ets>. Cf. <er>Fritter</er>.]</ety> <def>To
cook in a pan or on a griddle (esp. with the use of fat, butter, or
olive oil) by heating over a fire; to cook in boiling lard or fat;
<as>as, to <ex>fry</ex> fish; to <ex>fry</ex> doughnuts.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Fry
<hw>Fry</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To undergo the process
of frying; to be subject to the action of heat in a frying pan, or on a
griddle, or in a kettle of hot fat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To simmer; to boil.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With crackling flames a caldron <qex>fries</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The frothy billows <qex>fry</qex>.</q>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To undergo or cause a disturbing action accompanied
with a sensation of heat.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To keep the oil from <qex>frying</qex> in the stomach.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To be agitated; to be greatly moved.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What kindling motions in their breasts do <qex>fry</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Fry
<hw>Fry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A dish of anything
fried.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A state of excitement; <as>as, to be in a
<ex>fry</ex></as>.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fry</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Fry
<hw>Fry</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>fri</ets>, <ets>fry</ets>,
seed, descendants, cf. OF. <ets>froye</ets> spawning, spawn of. fishes,
little fishes, fr. L. <ets>fricare</ets> tosub (see <er>Friction</er>),
but cf. also Icel. <ets>fr⟦ae⟧</ets>, <ets>frj⟦omac⟧</ets>, seed, Sw. &
Dan. <ets>fr⟦oum⟧</ets>, Goth. <ets>fraiw</ets> seed,
descendants.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The young of any fish.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A swarm or crowd, especially of little fishes; young
or small things in general.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>fry</qex> of children young.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To sever . . . the good fish from the other <qex>fry</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>We have burned two frigates, and a hundred and twenty small
<qex>fry</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Walpole.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fryer</ent>⟦br⟧
